The context window is usually described as a scarce resource. Make it larger, the argument goes, and an AI can remember more. That sounds unambiguously useful until the conversation changes direction.

I have watched an agent finish one line of reasoning, receive a clear pivot, and continue answering as if the new request were another detail inside the old task. Nothing was forgotten. That was the problem. The earlier trajectory remained so available that the model mistook continuity of conversation for continuity of intent.

This is not just an anecdotal failure. A 2024 EMNLP [study of task interference](https://aclanthology.org/2024.emnlp-main.811/) tested 15 task switches across five datasets and found that irrelevant conversational history could significantly degrade performance. Persistent memory solves forgetting. It also creates **contextual inertia**.

## Memory is not the same as a working set

Long-running agents need two different things that are often collapsed into one: an immutable history of what happened and a working set for what matters now.

The full conversation has future value. Decisions, corrections, source documents, and unfinished work may all become relevant again. But availability should not imply equal authority. When the user switches from debugging a deployment to questioning the product strategy, the prior task should remain recoverable without continuing to steer the answer.

Garbage collection is a useful but incomplete analogy. A collector traces what is live and reclaims the rest. Old context is rarely garbage, and deleting it would destroy provenance. The system needs to change what is active without pretending the inactive history never existed.

The scarce resource is not storage. It is semantic authority.

## Context tools manage volume better than intent

Current systems solve important parts of this problem. [Anthropic's context editing](https://platform.claude.com/docs/en/build-with-claude/context-editing) can clear stale tool results and thinking blocks while the client retains the original history. [OpenAI's compaction](https://developers.openai.com/api/docs/guides/compaction) carries prior state into a smaller representation for subsequent turns. Both reduce context pressure.

But removing old tool output and compressing a transcript are mostly answers to a quantity problem. They do not necessarily decide what the latest message does to the authority of everything before it.

A 2026 paper on [intent mismatch in multi-turn conversation](https://arxiv.org/abs/2602.07338) gets closer. It separates intent understanding from task execution through a mediator that rewrites an evolving conversation into an explicit instruction for the assistant. That suggests the missing layer is not a novel memory store. It is an intent-aware context compiler that combines several existing ideas:

1. Read the new message without assuming the prior task still governs it.
2. Classify the transition: continue, revise, challenge, branch, replace, or resume.
3. Preserve durable residue such as accepted decisions, corrections, and unfinished obligations.
4. Retrieve evidence relevant to the newly inferred task.
5. Compile a disposable working set for the main model.

## The cold-read test

The first step supports a useful check: **if no prior task were active, what would this message appear to ask?**

The system can compare that cold reading with a continuity-aware interpretation. A large disagreement is evidence that history may be distorting intent. The new turn might be a critique of the current path, while the inherited context makes it look like a request to refine that path.

This is also where context management touches sycophancy. The familiar version of sycophancy preserves the user's framing too readily. A persistent agent can preserve the _joint trajectory_ too readily, including its own previous claims and plans. It favors narrative consistency over recognizing that new evidence changed the task.

The result is not simple agreement. It is trajectory-preserving agreement.

## The compiler can become a hidden editor of reality

This middle layer creates its own risk. A fast model that decides what the main model sees can remove inconvenient evidence, elevate a tentative idea into durable fact, or retrieve a similar old memory that silently pulls the conversation back into its previous lane. Aggressive compression can erase uncertainty, dissent, and reversals while leaving behind a falsely coherent summary.

I think a trustworthy version needs four properties:

1. The original event history remains immutable.
2. Compiled context is disposable and reconstructable.
3. Promotions, evictions, retrievals, and supersessions retain provenance.
4. The main model can follow a compressed claim back to primary evidence.

Semantic similarity is not enough. The compiler has to reason about authority, freshness, task state, contradiction, and whether an earlier decision was accepted, tentative, or superseded. Its limitation is structural: the component meant to prevent context bias can introduce a new bias before the main model ever sees the evidence.

## Continuous conversation, selective activation

I still think continuous project conversation is the better user experience. Starting a new chat for every task makes the human act as a context compiler: remember the prior discussion, decide what matters, preserve nuance, and restate it without introducing errors. The system saves tokens by exporting cognitive labor to the user.

The better split is continuous history for the person and selective activation for the model. In my own OpenClaw environment, persistent files, retrieval, compaction, and workflow state approximate parts of this pattern. The gaps become most visible during a pivot, when durable workflow state can remain operationally important without deserving control over the current conversation.

Larger context windows make history cheaper to retain. They do not make that history easier to govern. The useful measure of a persistent agent is whether it can preserve the record while recognizing when an earlier trajectory no longer has authority over the task at hand.
